{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473512"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:09:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:09:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2479"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2479"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.06,0.01,0.14,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2479"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51754"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2479"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2479"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37051"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"696"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2138"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2155"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14578"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51754"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of central colicky abdominal pain. He has no nausea, vomiting, fever, or cough. He reports mild joint pain over the past two days. He has no significant medical history and his immunisations are up to date. His parent explains that he has recently been unwell with coryzal symptoms for the past few weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. His abdomen is diffusely tender with no localising signs, rigidity, or guarding. He has no pitting oedema or facial swelling. There is a palpable purpuric rash distributed on the buttocks and legs bilaterally. Urinalysis reveals microscopic haematuria.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IgA vasculitis","Streptococcal infection","Crohn\u0027s disease","Immune thrombocytopenic purpura","Granulomatosis with polyangiitis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely has \u003Cstrong\u003EIgA vasculitis\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as Henoch-Schonlein purpura (HSP). The diagnosis is based on the classic triad of abdominal pain, joint pain, and palpable purpuric rash distributed on the buttocks and legs bilaterally. The presence of microscopic haematuria and a recent upper respiratory infection further support this diagnosis. HSP typically affects children between two and 11 years old and often follows a viral illness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcal infection\u003C/strong\u003E can cause complications such as scarlet fever (rash), post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis, and rheumatic fever. However, it is unlikely to cause all the symptoms present in this patient, particularly the characteristic palpable purpura and joint pain without fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E can cause abdominal pain and extraintestinal manifestations such as erythema nodosum. However, erythema nodosum presents as tender red bumps and nodules under the skin, often on the lower legs, which differs from the palpable purpuric rash seen in this patient. Additionally, Crohn\u0027s disease typically has a more gradual onset and is not associated with recent viral illnesses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmune thrombocytopenic purpura\u003C/strong\u003E (ITP) can cause a purpuric rash due to low platelet count. However, ITP is unlikely to cause joint and abdominal pain. The purpura in ITP is typically non-palpable, unlike the palpable purpura seen in HSP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulomatosis with polyangiitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammatory condition that primarily affects the blood vessels in the upper respiratory tract, lungs, and kidneys. While it can present with joint pain, palpable purpura, and haematuria, it typically affects older individuals and is associated with respiratory symptoms such as sinusitis or shortness of breath, which are absent in this case. The presence of abdominal pain and the patient\u0027s age make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, the combination of recent viral illness, abdominal pain, joint pain, palpable purpura on the lower limbs, and microscopic haematuria in a child strongly suggests IgA vasculitis as the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["IgA vasculitis typically presents with abdominal pain, joint pain, and palpable purpura on the lower limbs, often following a recent viral illness.","Microscopic haematuria is a common finding in IgA vasculitis and indicates renal involvement."],"references":["Reamy BV, Servey JT, Williams PM. Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein Purpura (IgA Vasculitis): Rapid Evidence Review. Am Fam Physician. 2020 Aug 15;102(4):229-233. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2020/0815/p229.html","Roache-Robinson P, Hotwagner DT. Henoch Sch\u00f6nlein Purpura. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2022. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537252/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37051"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2479"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37051"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-28T16:13:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-28T16:18:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2479"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51754"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type